<div class="markdown"><h2>So what does this class do?</h2><h3>Data Science:</h3><ul><li><p>Develop <em>Data Acumen</em><a class="footnote" href="#footnote-1">[1]</a></p><ul><li><p>Model building</p></li><li><p>Data visualization</p></li><li><p>Reproducible research</p></li></ul></li><li><p>Practice "soft skills"</p><ul><li><p>Technical collaboration</p></li><li><p>Effective visualization</p></li><li><p>Scientific communications</p></li></ul></li><li><p>Provide taste of Data Science</p></li></ul></div>


<div class="markdown"><h3>Data Acumen</h3><div class="footnote" id="footnote-1"><p class="footnote-title">1</p><p>"We define data acumen as the ability to make good judgements about the use of data to support problem solutions." (<a href="https://doi.org/10.1162/99608f92.2d83f7f5">Keller et al. 2020</a>)</p></div></div>


<div class="markdown"><h3>Along the way...</h3><p>You'll learn and/or reinforce foundational concepts that are covered in much more detail in other courses:</p><ul><li><p>Programming (build experience, likely a new language)</p></li><li><p>Numerical Methods (e.g., integration, sampling)</p></li><li><p>Linear Algebra (e.g., solving linear systems)</p></li><li><p>Statistics (e.g., likelihood, priors, distributions) </p></li><li><p>Machine Learning (e.g., optimization)</p></li><li><p>Astronomical Techniques (e.g., observational biases)</p></li></ul></div>


<div class="markdown"><h1>Course Overview</h1><p>Students will build practical data science skills (e.g., querying astronomical databases, data storage and manipulation, data visualization, exploratory and explanatory data analysis, Bayesian modeling workflows, and reproducible research practices) and apply these lessons to analyzing data from astronomical surveys.</p><h2>Goals</h2><ul><li><p>Increase their data acumen, and</p></li><li><p>Appreciate how building data science skills can benefit astronomy &amp; astrophysics research.</p></li></ul><h2>Objectives</h2><ul><li><p>Ingest and manipulate data from astronomical surveys.</p></li><li><p>Build, apply, assess and update astrophysically motivated models for astronomical observations.</p></li><li><p>Create visualizations for exploratory and explanatory data analyses of observations from astronomical surveys.</p></li><li><p>Synthesize the above into a dashboard to support the efficient analysis of astronomical observations.</p></li><li><p>Incorporate principles of reproducible research into their class project.</p></li></ul></div>

<div class="markdown"><h1>Philosophy of Data Analysis</h1></div>


<div class="markdown"><h2>What's the goal of an analysis?</h2><h2>Example Goals</h2><ul><li><p>Test a precisely formulated hypothesis </p></li><li><p>Make predicitons with an well-established model</p></li><li><p>Make predictions, but you don't (yet?) have a trustworthy model</p></li><li><p>Refine an exisiting model with additional data</p></li><li><p>Compare multiple competing models to gain physical insight</p></li><li><p>Compare multiple models to pick one to use for making predictions </p></li><li><p>Take a first look at a new dataset and find something interesting</p></li><li><p>Prioritize what portions of analysis will require the most attention</p></li></ul><h4>Different Goals require Different Approaches</h4></div>


<div class="markdown"><h2>Prototypical Approaches</h2><h4>Tradditional physics/first-principles approach</h4><ul><li><p>Start with a model we trust</p></li><li><p>Add data to infer model parameters</p></li></ul><h4>Machine learning/Data-driven approach</h4><ul><li><p>Start with large dataset</p></li><li><p>Find a model that would have made good predictions</p></li></ul></div>


<div class="markdown"><h2>Limitations of the Prototypical Approaches</h2><h4>First-principles approach</h4><ul><li><p>Start with a <strong>model we trust</strong></p></li><li><p>Add data to infer model parameters</p></li></ul><h4>Machine learning/Data-driven approach</h4><ul><li><p>Start with <strong>large</strong> dataset</p></li><li><p>Find a model that <strong>would have</strong> made <strong>good</strong> predictions</p></li></ul></div>


<div class="markdown"><h2>Prototypical Astronomical Problem</h2><ul><li><p>Significant astrophysical knowledge</p><ul><li><p>but model is an approximation &amp; incomplete</p></li></ul></li><li><p>Significant quantity of data</p><ul><li><p>observing time is limited,</p></li><li><p>data collection process is complicated, and</p></li><li><p>constantly pushing limits of capabilities.</p></li></ul></li></ul><h4>How can we integrate these effectively?</h4><ul><li><p>What tool(s) are best for our task?</p></li><li><p>Learning to apply an existing tool to data is (usually) relatively straightforward. </p></li><li><p>Developing experience to apply tools wisely is more challenging.  </p></li><li><p>Acquiring the breath of experience to choose best tools for a task is a lifetime of learning.</p></li></ul></div>
